To set up **Nix-on-Droid** with **Home Manager** using a Flake, you need to configure your `flake.nix` to include `nix-on-droid` and `home-manager` as inputs, then use the `nix-on-droid` module system to integrate them[1][2].

### Example `flake.nix`

This structure allows you to manage both your Nix-on-Droid system configuration and your Home Manager user environment declaratively[3][2].

```nix
{
  description = "Nix-on-Droid with Home Manager Flake";

  inputs = {
    nixpkgs.url = "github:NixOS/nixpkgs/nixos-unstable";

    nix-on-droid = {
      url = "github:nix-community/nix-on-droid/release-24.05";
      inputs.nixpkgs.follows = "nixpkgs";
    };

    home-manager = {
      url = "github:nix-community/home-manager/release-24.05";
      inputs.nixpkgs.follows = "nixpkgs";
    };
  };

  outputs = { self, nixpkgs, nix-on-droid, home-manager }: {
    nixOnDroidConfigurations.default = nix-on-droid.lib.nixOnDroidConfiguration {
      modules = [
        ./nix-on-droid.nix
        home-manager.nixosModules.home-manager
        {
          home-manager.useGlobalPkgs = true;
          home-manager.useUserPackages = true;
          home-manager.config = ./home.nix;
        }
      ];
    };
  };
}
```

### Configuration Files

1.  **`nix-on-droid.nix`**: Place your system-level settings here (e.g., core packages, shell, or terminal configuration)[1].
    ```nix
    { pkgs, ... }: {
      environment.packages = [ pkgs.vim pkgs.git ];
      system.stateVersion = "24.05";
    }
    ```

2.  **`home.nix`**: Define your user-specific environment (e.g., dotfiles, shell aliases, user-specific packages)[4][5].
    ```nix
    { pkgs, ... }: {
      home.username = "nix-on-droid";
      home.homeDirectory = "/data/data/com.termux.nix/files/home";
      home.stateVersion = "24.05";

      programs.bash.enable = true;
      home.packages = [ pkgs.htop ];
    }
    ```

### How to Apply
To build and activate your configuration, run the following command in the directory containing your `flake.nix`:

```bash
nix-on-droid switch --flake .
```

*Note: Because of how `proot` is handled in Nix-on-Droid, you may need to use the `--impure` flag if you encounter errors regarding hardcoded store paths[1].*

